AN  - 754041442; 201053289
AB  - Draws on various secondary sources to examine how anti-Communism & homophobia in the late-Cold War US impacted Cuban & US immigration policies. The gay press's relationship to the larger narrative of the 1980 Mariel boatlift is explored, asserting that the gay press & the US homosexual community helped mobilize queer resistance & support for the Marielitos. In considering the experiences of these Cuban exiles, light is shed on the relationships among immigration, nationality, & sexuality. In particular, the effect of the Refugee Act of 1980 on the Marielitos is discussed in terms of the "state's gaze" on homosexuality. It is contended that the US shifted its homophobic stance on immigration & citizenship in support of those fleeing Cuban Communism. D. Edelman
